bservational studies conducted twenty-six years apart, Martín Sánchez-Jankowski documents the process of ethnic school violence from start to finish. In addition to shedding light on what causes this type of violence and how it progresses over time, Burning Dislike provides strategic policy suggestions to address this troubling phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnic conflictzUnited States. 0aHigh schoolsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSchool violencezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aafrican american students.  aamerican public schools.  aeducation safety.  aeducation.  aethnic conflict in high schools.  aethnic conflict.  aethnic school violence.  aethnic studies.  ahigh schools in america.  ahigh schools tensions.  aidentifying violence in schools.  ain school violence.  ainterethnic aggressions in high school.  apreventing violence in schools.  aviolence in schools.  aviolent interactions in american high schools.  ayouth violence in schools.  ayouth violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978052028919240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096387040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963870/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY